Every web developer, at some point in their journey, runs into the dreaded browser wall:
Access to XMLHttpRequest at 'http://localhost:8080/api/users' from origin 'http://localhost:4200' has been blocked by CORS policy.
It is a rite of passage. You have a shiny Angular frontend running on port 4200 and a robust Java backend (likely Spring Boot) running on port 8080. They are both on your machine, yet the browser treats them like hostile foreign entities.
Let’s dissect exactly why this happens and explore the concrete ways to fix it on both the Angular frontend and the Java backend.
The Anatomy of the Problem: Why the Browser Blocks You
Before writing code, we need to understand the Same-Origin Policy (SOP). The browser enforces this security mechanism to prevent malicious websites from reading data from another site without permission.
An Origin is defined by three things: Protocol, Domain, and Port.

• http://localhost:4200 (Angular)

• http://localhost:8080 (Java API)
Because the ports (4200 vs 8080) do not match, they are considered entirely different origins. When Angular requests data, the browser sends the request but intercepts the response. If the Java backend doesn't explicitly return the correct headers saying "Hey, I trust port 4200!", the browser throws a CORS error and hides the data from your Javascript code.
Strategy 1: The Frontend Illusion (Angular Dev Proxy)
The cleanest way to handle this during local development is to trick the browser into thinking the frontend and backend share the exact same origin. We do this using Angular’s built-in development proxy.
Step 1: Create proxy.conf.json
In the root directory of your Angular project (right next to package.json), create a file named proxy.conf.json:
{
"/api": {
"target": "http://localhost:8080",
"secure": false,
"changeOrigin": true,
"logLevel": "debug"
}
}Step 2: Register it in angular.json
Find your project’s architect -> serve configuration block and point it to your new proxy file
"architect": {
"serve": {
"options": {
"proxyConfig": "proxy.conf.json"
}
}
}Step 3: Use Relative Paths
In your Angular services, stop hardcoding http://localhost:8080. Instead, use a relative path:
// Angular Service
this.http.get('/api/users').subscribe(...);When you run ng serve, Angular intercepts any request starting with /api and forwards it behind the scenes to your Java backend on port 8080. The browser only ever sees requests going to port 4200, eliminating CORS altogether.
Strategy 2: The Backend Authorization (Java / Spring Boot)
If your app is deployed across different cloud domains in production, or if you prefer to solve this on the backend, Java gives you three primary entry points to grant origin permissions.
Option A: The Quick Fix (@CrossOrigin)
If you only have a few controllers causing issues, annotate them directly.
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users")
@CrossOrigin(origins = "http://localhost:4200")
public class UserController { @GetMapping
public ResponseEntity<List<User>> getAllUsers() {
return ResponseEntity.ok(userService.getAll());
}
}
Option B: The Global MVC Configurer (Recommended)
For global configuration without cluttering your code with annotations, define a dedicated WebMvcConfigurer bean.
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.web.servlet.config.annotation.CorsRegistry;
import org.springframework.web.servlet.config.annotation.WebMvcConfigurer;@Configuration
public class WebCorsConfig {
@Bean
public WebMvcConfigurer corsConfigurer() {
return new WebMvcConfigurer() {
@Override
public void addCorsMappings(CorsRegistry registry) {
registry.addMapping("/**") // Match all endpoints
.allowedOrigins("http://localhost:4200", "https://production-frontend.com")
.allowedMethods("GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE", "OPTIONS")
.allowedHeaders("*")
.allowCredentials(true);
}
};
}
}
Strategy 3: The Spring Security Trap
If your Java backend includes Spring Security, Options A and B will fail silently.
Spring Security acts as a filter chain that sits in front of your MVC Controllers. When an Angular application makes a request with custom headers (like an Authorization Bearer token), the browser sends a hidden preliminary request called an OPTIONS preflight.
Spring Security catches this unauthenticated OPTIONS request, flags it as unauthorized, and blocks it before it ever reaches your MVC CORS configuration.
To bypass this, you must explicitly pass the CORS configurations directly into the SecurityFilterChain:
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.security.config.annotation.web.builders.HttpSecurity;
import org.springframework.security.web.SecurityFilterChain;
import org.springframework.web.cors.CorsConfiguration;
import java.util.List;@Configuration
public class SecurityConfig {
@Bean
public SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
http
.cors(cors -> cors.configurationSource(request -> {
CorsConfiguration config = new CorsConfiguration();
config.setAllowedOrigins(List.of("http://localhost:4200"));
config.setAllowedMethods(List.of("GET", "POST", "PUT", "DELETE", "OPTIONS"));
config.setAllowedHeaders(List.of("*"));
config.setAllowCredentials(true);
return config;
}))
.csrf(csrf -> csrf.disable()) // Only do this for specific APIs / Dev testing
.authorizeHttpRequests(auth -> auth
.anyRequest().authenticated()
);
return http.build();
}
}
Verification: Knowing When You’ve Won
To ensure your fix worked, crack open your browser’s Developer Tools (F12) and head to the Network tab. Click on your API network request and examine the Response Headers.
If successful, you will see:

• Access-Control-Allow-Origin: http://localhost:4200

• Access-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, POST, ...
If these headers are present, the browser will drop its shields, allow the network traffic to flow freely, and your Angular app will render its components smoothly.
The Single-Domain Setup (The “No-CORS” Standard)
In enterprise production environments, the most common practice is to completely eliminate CORS by placing both the frontend and the backend behind a Reverse Proxy or API Gateway (like Nginx, AWS CloudFront, Cloudflare, or an Application Load Balancer).Developers don’t hardcode full URLs like https://api.example.com. Instead, they use relative paths:
In this setup, everything is served under a single domain:

• Frontend: https://my-app.com/

• Backend: https://my-app.com/api/...
Because the domain, protocol, and port are identical, the browser views this as the Same-Origin. CORS is never triggered, meaning you don’t have to configure any CORS settings in Java!
How it works with Nginx (Production Example):
When a user goes to https://my-app.com, the request hits your Nginx server. Nginx acts as a traffic cop:
server {
listen 443 ssl;
server_name my-app.com;# 1. Route static frontend requests to Angular files
location / {
root /var/www/angular-app;
try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
}
# 2. Route API requests to the Java Backend running on port 8080
location /api {
proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
proxy_set_header Host $host;
proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
}
}
